                <h1 style="color: var(--color-primary); margin: var(--space-4) 0;" class="wiley-hero-title">Lesson 3.1: How Local Government Works</h1>
                <h2 style="color: var(--color-secondary); margin: 0.5rem 0; font-weight: normal;" class="wiley-section-title">The System That Shapes Your Neighbourhood</h2>
                <p style="color: var(--color-text-secondary); font-size: var(--text-lg);">Students learn about the role and responsibilities of local councils, exploring how these systems directly impact their daily lives, from the parks they play in to the water they drink.</p>
            </div>

            <section style="background: linear-gradient(135deg, var(--color-secondary) 0%, var(--color-primary) 100%); color: white; padding: var(--space-8); border-radius: var(--radius-lg); margin-bottom: 2rem;">
                <h2 style="color: white; margin-bottom: 1rem;" class="wiley-section-title">Whakatūwhera - Cultural Opening</h2>
                <p style="line-height: 1.7; margin-bottom: 1rem;">The principle of `kaitiakitanga` teaches us that we all have a responsibility to be guardians of our place—our `whenua`. Local government is the system our community uses to practice kaitiakitanga. It's how we collectively care for our environment, our resources, and the wellbeing of everyone who lives here. Today we explore this system to understand how it works, and how we can be part of it.</p>
            

